2026-04-16 12:14:28 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['ambient sensor / control module internal relay or driver circuitry'] hypothesis_explanation='The power supply is healthy (LED on, 12 V present at control-module input with correct polarity). Yet the control module output never provides the expected 12 V: it sits around 0.36 V on the supposed + line and ~0 V on the − line, even when the sensor is manipulated and the timing potentiometer is swept over its entire range. The lamp’s behavior (brief outages every ~20 s, now not lighting during recent tests) is consistent with the relay/driver intermittently or permanently failing to close and passing only a small leakage voltage. Since the input is correct and the downstream load module is passive apart from its diode and bulbs, the only plausible root cause is a fault within the ambient sensor/control module’s switching path (relay contacts, relay coil drive transistor, or associated control electronics). Replacing or repairing the internal relay/driver circuitry of the control module should restore proper 12 V switching to the load.'
