2026-04-16 12:15:15 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['control module internal ground / negative-rail connection (between sensor/logic section and negative output cable)'] hypothesis_explanation='The PSU reliably provides ~12 V (11.99 V) referenced to its 0 V line. This same 12 V appears at the control‑module input, so the cabling and PSU are sound. At the relay, the measured terminals show about 11.63 V across the coil (11.99 V vs 0.36 V), indicating the relay coil and its driver are correctly powered from the supply rails and are operating normally. \n\nHowever, at the light sensor / logic section inside the control module, the positive node is only ~0.119 V above the negative node (~0.0003 V). That means the sensor/logic circuit does *not* see the 12 V rail that exists at the relay section. Since the control logic is the only path that can energize and de‑energize the relay over time, the fact that it is essentially unpowered (only ~0.12 V) explains why the timing potentiometer sweep has no effect and why earlier behavior (20 s flicker) was erratic: the control electronics intermittently lost their proper supply reference. \n\nThe combination of: (1) good 12 V at the module input; (2) good 12 V across the relay coil; (3) almost zero volts across the sensor/logic supply; and (4) repaired/verified non‑faulty relay/driver, strongly points to a fault in the internal negative (ground) distribution of the control module—specifically the connection tying the sensor/logic negative rail to the module’s main negative/output cable. If this internal ground connection is open, high‑resistance, or miswired, the relay section can still get a return path (hence its nearly full supply), while the sensor/logic section floats near 0 V and never receives proper supply voltage.\n\nTherefore the most plausible root cause is a faulty internal ground/negative‑rail connection inside the control module, between the sensor/logic section and the module’s negative output/return. Repairing or reworking that internal negative‑rail connection should restore full ~12 V to the sensor/logic, letting the timing and sensitivity control the relay and stopping the unexplained lamp outages.'
